    },
    {
      "id": "6023577ee8626c47e18eae3212e58de982eceeba",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2025-01-14 16:05:14.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1\n\nThe reason for this was due to the native Linux client. So for the case of --disable-modules we shouldn't have the UAPI headers in lustre-dev. Now if we do want the out of tree modules then yes the UAPI headers should be installed. In that case they will installed with kernel modules. Are you only install lustre-dev without a native Linux client?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "cb8d550388e249bd48b3b6526c087462c9381cb2",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 793,
        "name": "Aurelien Degremont",
        "email": "adegremont@nvidia.com",
        "username": "degremoa"
      },
      "date": "2025-01-14 16:26:40.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n> Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1\n> \n> The reason for this was due to the native Linux client. So for the case of --disable-modules we shouldn't have the UAPI headers in lustre-dev. Now if we do want the out of tree modules then yes the UAPI headers should be installed. In that case they will installed with kernel modules. Are you only install lustre-dev without a native Linux client?\n\nI'm confused. Could you explain that more in details?\n My problem is when using DKMS modules for Debian packages. The uapi headers are not packaged anywhere in this scenario.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "0265d9822e10155475b299289482a056c710a7e1",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 793,
        "name": "Aurelien Degremont",
        "email": "adegremont@nvidia.com",
        "username": "degremoa"
      },
      "date": "2025-01-14 16:51:45.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n> Patch Set 2:\n> \n> > Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1\n> > \n> > The reason for this was due to the native Linux client. So for the case of --disable-modules we shouldn't have the UAPI headers in lustre-dev. Now if we do want the out of tree modules then yes the UAPI headers should be installed. In that case they will installed with kernel modules. Are you only install lustre-dev without a native Linux client?\n> \n> I'm confused. Could you explain that more in details?\n> My problem is when using DKMS modules for Debian packages. The uapi headers are not packaged anywhere in this scenario.\n\nWe have 3 use cases:\n* in-kernel modules\n* outside of kernel modules\n* dkms\n\nPlease double check, but I think i'm doing what RPMS are doing.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "def8cde73f02c9af60f393e26b310358afb39cca",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
        "name": "Maloo",
        "email": "maloo@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2025-01-14 18:45:35.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Verified+1\n\nPassed enforced test review-ldiskfs-dne on RHEL 9.4 / x86_64 uploaded by Trevis Autotest from trevis-129vm1: https://testing.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/40b1c30f-bfdb-4966-8b10-8d3214f49d07 ran 5 tests.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "fd0f5c516442b93dcaed1622d1db30bb9761604f",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 793,
        "name": "Aurelien Degremont",
        "email": "adegremont@nvidia.com",
        "username": "degremoa"
      },
      "date": "2025-01-15 09:33:48.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nJames, looking at this again, i think there is some confusion here. After checking the RPMs packages, there are exactly doing what I'm proposing for .deb packages. By example, there are no headers, in the kmod-lustre-client-modules. There are in lustre-devel.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "3f8041fdc3e914f9fac82cdd9ef01cc3781ec108",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2025-01-17 01:29:21.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nIf you have a platform with native Linux client (remember Ubuntu was like that for years) then lustre-devel will not install due to conflicts with the already existing UAPI headers. That is why I suggest placing those UAPI headers in the kernel modules package instead.\n\nNote I plan on going to the Linux file system summit to discuss Lustre going into the kernel so the return of the Linux native client might be closer than you think.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "f63cd5b016b7dc3272b8b83f0c21f01c84a9a941",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 793,
        "name": "Aurelien Degremont",
        "email": "adegremont@nvidia.com",
        "username": "degremoa"
      },
      "date": "2025-01-17 13:47:49.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n> Patch Set 2:\n> \n> If you have a platform with native Linux client (remember Ubuntu was like that for years) then lustre-devel will not install due to conflicts with the already existing UAPI headers. That is why I suggest placing those UAPI headers in the kernel modules package instead.\n\n- So that means putting a copy of them in both module package and dkms package\n- But they will still conflict with whatever kernel package if the distro kernel is already including lustre files.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "a9651e6ab0b2c26302c523a57fd1737c86d06f51",
